                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d786">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11279: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Tsingtao</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sokobin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tsingtao</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-24T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >November 24, 1937—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 25—8:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Consulate has been informed by commander of British cruiser now in port who
                    visited Japanese refrigerating plant, part of which is now being used by British
                    firm, that engine room was loaded by Chinese last night with 60 pounds of
                    dynamite and other explosives ready to set off.</p>
                <p>I have been informed that the instruction of the Generalissimo to the Mayor in
                    regard to destruction of Japanese property was in translation “to take such
                    measures as the situation warrants.”</p>
                <p>Sent to Nanking, Peiping, Chefoo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sokobin</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
